    rationale='Routine vital signs, ambulation for a stable cleared postoperative client, and basic hygiene/meal assistance are appropriate CNA tasks. Wound assessment, insulin administration, and A1c interpretation require licensed nursing judgment and cannot be delegated to a CNA.',
    deep_rationale='Delegation questions test whether the RN can separate stable, routine, measurable tasks from work that requires assessment, teaching, medication administration, interpretation, or evaluation. This client is stable on postoperative day 2, so collecting routine vital signs, assisting with ambulation to the bathroom, and helping with oral hygiene and meal setup are appropriate CNA tasks when facility policy and supervision are in place. Assessing a surgical site is not just looking; it requires interpreting redness, drainage, swelling, warmth, and wound risk. Sliding-scale insulin is medication administration with hypoglycemia risk and requires licensed judgment. Interpreting A1c and adjusting insulin are clinical decision-making tasks. Clinical pearl: if the task requires assessment, teaching, evaluation, medication administration, or interpretation of clinical meaning, it stays with the RN or another appropriately licensed clinician.',
    references_json='[{"title":"NCSBN National Guidelines for Nursing Delegation","citation":"NCSBN delegation guidance describes the Five Rights of Delegation and emphasizes that the licensed nurse remains accountable for appropriate task selection, communication, supervision, and evaluation."},{"title":"Nursing Management and Professional Concepts - NCBI Bookshelf","citation":"The NCBI nursing delegation chapter summarizes NCSBN delegation principles, including right task, circumstance, person, direction/communication, and supervision/evaluation."},{"title":"NCSBN 2026 NCLEX-RN Test Plan","citation":"NCSBN 2026 RN Test Plan, Management of Care and Clinical Judgment."}]',
