    review_status='final-curated-live',
    rationale='The client has hypovolemic shock from active gastrointestinal bleeding. Priority nursing actions include restoring circulating volume with IV crystalloid while definitive therapy is arranged, keeping the client NPO for endoscopy or airway-risk procedures, and monitoring urine output as a perfusion marker.',
    deep_rationale='Hematemesis, melena, hypotension, tachycardia, low hemoglobin, diaphoresis, and altered mentation point to acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding with shock physiology. The immediate nursing priorities are circulation and preparation for definitive evaluation. IV crystalloid resuscitation supports blood pressure and organ perfusion while blood products, labs, and endoscopic management are being coordinated. NPO status reduces aspiration risk and prepares the client for urgent endoscopy or possible procedural sedation. Hourly urine output helps evaluate renal perfusion and response to resuscitation. A cold pack does not treat intravascular volume loss. Octreotide may be ordered when variceal bleeding is suspected, but the stem does not provide variceal-risk cues and it is not the broad first nursing priority over resuscitation. Oral antacid is inappropriate in an unstable NPO client with active bleeding. Clinical pearl: active GI bleed with hypotension is a circulation problem first; stabilize, prepare for endoscopy, and trend perfusion.',
    references_json='[{"title":"Merck Manual Professional - Overview of Gastrointestinal Bleeding","citation":"Merck Manual Professional describes hematemesis and melena as potential emergencies and includes IV fluid resuscitation as an initial management priority for significant GI bleeding."},{"title":"NCSBN 2026 NCLEX-RN Test Plan","citation":"NCSBN 2026 RN Test Plan, Physiological Adaptation, Management of Care, and Clinical Judgment."}]',
    deep_rationale_authored_at=unixepoch(),
    provenance=COALESCE(provenance,'gen') || '|editorial-batch-007:manual-source-backed-promote'
WHERE id='gen-nemotron-1780644622-1-nxvg5';

UPDATE questions
SET publish_state='published',
    review_status='final-curated-live',
    rationale='Ampicillin is a penicillin-class antibiotic, so a known penicillin allergy makes the order unsafe until clarified. The nurse should contact the prescriber, document the communication and resolution, and use the chain of command if the unsafe order is not corrected.',
    deep_rationale='Medication safety requires the nurse to check allergies before administration and to stop when a prescribed medication conflicts with a known allergy. Ampicillin is in the penicillin class, so administering it to a client with a documented penicillin allergy could cause serious hypersensitivity, including anaphylaxis. The first action is direct clarification with the prescribing clinician using clear allergy information. If the prescriber is unavailable or insists on an unsafe order, the nurse must escalate through the chain of command according to facility policy while continuing to protect the client. Documentation should capture the concern, who was contacted, the response, and the final resolution. Administering the medication while watching for a reaction is unsafe because prevention is the goal. Prophylactic diphenhydramine or epinephrine does not make a contraindicated antibiotic safe to give. Clinical pearl: allergy conflict equals stop, clarify, document, and escalate if needed.',
    references_json='[{"title":"ANA 2025 Code of Ethics for Nurses - Provisions","citation":"The ANA Code of Ethics provisions describe the nurse''s duty to advocate for the health and safety of recipients of nursing care and uphold professional accountability."},{"title":"NCSBN 2026 NCLEX-RN Test Plan","citation":"NCSBN 2026 RN Test Plan, Pharmacological and Parenteral Therapies, Safety and Infection Control, and Clinical Judgment."}]',
    deep_rationale_authored_at=unixepoch(),
    provenance=COALESCE(provenance,'gen') || '|editorial-batch-007:manual-source-backed-promote'
WHERE id='gen-gemini-1780644622-2-ee6ri';

