SET publish_state='published',
    review_status='final-curated-live',
    rationale='A fetal heart rate baseline of 130 bpm with moderate variability, accelerations present, and no decelerations is Category I and reassuring. There is no absent variability, late deceleration pattern, or fetal-distress cue requiring immediate intervention.',
    deep_rationale='Category I fetal heart rate tracings are strongly associated with normal fetal acid-base status at the time observed. This strip has a normal baseline rate of 130 bpm, moderate variability, accelerations, and no decelerations. Moderate variability is one of the strongest reassuring features because it reflects intact fetal neurologic and oxygenation status. Accelerations may be present or absent in Category I, but when present they add reassurance. The tracing is not Category II or III because there are no late decelerations, recurrent variable decelerations, bradycardia, tachycardia, or absent variability. The appropriate interpretation is routine ongoing observation rather than immediate intrauterine resuscitation. Clinical pearl: moderate variability plus no late or variable decelerations is reassuring; do not overcall fetal distress when the objective strip is Category I.',
    references_json='[{"title":"AHRQ Perinatal Safety - Electronic Fetal Monitoring","citation":"AHRQ summarizes Category I criteria as baseline 110-160 bpm, moderate variability, accelerations present or absent, and absent late or variable decelerations, with no specific action required."},{"title":"NICHD Workshop Review on Standardized Fetal Heart Rate Nomenclature","citation":"The NICHD three-tier system describes Category I tracings as baseline 110-160 bpm, moderate variability, absent late or variable decelerations, with early decelerations and accelerations either present or absent."},{"title":"NCSBN 2026 NCLEX-RN Test Plan","citation":"NCSBN 2026 RN Test Plan, Health Promotion and Maintenance and Clinical Judgment."}]',
